{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486798"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:45:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:45:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"179"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/179"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.45,0.17,0.13,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"179"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105986"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/179"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2019-09-26T01:35:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-15T18:04:11+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2024-01-23T06:28:08+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-26 18:55:24"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"179"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"16432"}},"author":{"data":null},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88461"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"629"},{"type":"contributions","id":"828"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9989"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10692"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10705"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12964"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15177"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15568"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33126"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38926"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42019"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42977"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88461"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105986"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 86-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of shortness of breath and ankle swelling. The dyspnoea was previously only on exercise, but now it is also present at rest. She has a history of chronic kidney disease and hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her blood pressure is 139/90 mmHg, pulse 88/min, temperature 37.4\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and respiratory rate 21/min. She has bi-basal crepitations and pitting oedema to her knees. A recently tested creatinine was found to be 101 \u00b5mol/L (45\u201384) and potassium was 5.2 mmol/L (3.5\u20135.3).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn echocardiogram is conducted and reported as \u0027\u003Cem\u003EEjection fraction 36% with regional wall motion abnormalities, dilated left ventricle, mild-moderate tricuspid regurgitation, pulmonary artery systolic pressure of 25mmHg.\u0027\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following drug combinations would be most appropriate initial management for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atenolol, perindopril, spironolactone","Perindopril, frusemide, dapagliflozin","Metoprolol (immediate release), perindopril, furosemide","Bisoprolol, furosemide, perindopril","Amlodipine, perindopril, spironolactone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has the signs and symptoms of congestive heart failure, specifically - heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF) seen on echocardiogram with the ejection fraction below 40%. The patient is at a higher risk of this condition as she is elderly. The worsening dyspnoea, signs of oedema (up to the knees in this case), and crepitations (from pleural effusions) all are classic manifestations of heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of \u003Cstrong\u003Eperindopril, frusemide, and dapagliflozin\u003C/strong\u003E is most appropriate as initial therapy. ACE inhibitors are a cornerstone of heart failure management and can be started concurrently with diuretics. SGLT2 inhibitors like dapagliflozin have shown significant mortality benefit in heart failure and can be initiated early in therapy. Frusemide is indicated as the patient currently has symptoms of fluid overload which will help shift this excess fluid and return the patient to a euvolaemic state. Whilst frusemide does not have a mortality benefit in heart failure, it is a critical component to managing symptoms of fluid overload and reducing patient morbidity. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other answers have various incorrect components:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u0392 blockers such as \u003Cstrong\u003Ebisoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E should only be commenced once the patient is euvolaemic, as starting them during acute decompensation can worsen heart failure symptoms. This patient has significant fluid overload evidenced by bilateral crepitations and extensive oedema. Additionally \u003Cstrong\u003Emetoprolol immediate-release \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Eatenolol\u003C/strong\u003E are not an appropriate heart failure specific beta-blockers (though extended-release formulation of metoprolol can be used).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpironolactone\u003C/strong\u003E poses a risk of hyperkalaemia when combined with an ACE inhibitor and requires careful monitoring of renal function. Due to the patient\u0027s borderline hyperkalaemia (and chronic kidney disease), spironolactone is not recommended at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce the patient is stabilised and euvolaemic, additional evidence-based medications including a heart failure specific beta-blocker and mineralocorticoid receptor antagonist (if potassium and renal function permit) can be considered to optimise therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Initial heart failure management should consist of an ACE inhibitor or ARNI, and diuretic therapy to achieve euvolaemic status.","Heart failure specific beta-blockers (bisoprolol, carvedilol, nebivolol, metoprolol XR) should only be commenced once euvolaemic status is achieved.","A mineralcorticoid receptor antagonist and SGLT2 inhibitor can be added to optimise heart failure therapy, considering renal function and potassium levels."],"references":["Atherton J, Sindone A, O\u0027Loughlin J, Branagan M. National Heart Foundation of Australia and Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Guidelines for the Prevention, Detection, and Management of Heart Failure in Australia 2018. Heart Lung and Circulation. 2020;27(10):1123-1208. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30077227/","Murphy SP, Ibrahim NE, Januzzi JL Jr. Heart Failure With Reduced Ejection Fraction: A Review. JAMA. 2020 Aug 4;324(5):488-504. doi: 10.1001/jama.2020.10262. PMID: 32749493. Available at: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/article-abstract/2768982"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88461"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"179"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88461"},"attribut